Lessons that can be learned today from the Cuban Crisis
„Thirteen Days” („Dreizehn Tage“), a new film about the Cuban Crisis, will soon be released in cinemas across many countries.
Everyone should see this work, not only because the film deals with the past, but also because it provides insights into current events – especially regarding the controversies surrounding an American national missile defense system and the various regional discussions in India and Pakistan, Taiwan and China, North and South Korea, which could one day escalate into a nuclear conflict.
On October 16, 1962, President John F. Kennedy summoned his closest advisors to the White House.
Aerial photographs of the area had revealed the construction of a nuclear weapons installation on Cuba.
The decisions made in the following thirteen days, and the decisions that were not made, could have led to the outbreak of a nuclear war.
The film illustrates what happened in the White House during those days.
Recordings made during Kennedy's presidency played a major role in the creation of the film.
After the film's premiere in America, the Kennedy School of Government at Harvard organized a discussion panel to discuss the film as well as the crisis it deals with.
Participants in this panel included, among others: Robert McNamara, Defense Secretary under President Kennedy; Theodore Sorensen, a close advisor and speechwriter for Kennedy; Ernest R. May, a history professor at Harvard who wrote a book about the "Kennedy Tapes"; and finally Graham Allison, a political science professor at Harvard who presented a classic study on the Cuban Crisis thirty years ago, the work "Essence of Decision".
In addition, Peter A. Almond, the film's producer, was also present.
Although the film's treatment of the subject was criticized in several respects, the participants in the discussion were able to agree that the film accurately portrays the problems and pressure that President Kennedy faced.
What lessons can be drawn today from the Cuban Crisis?
Theodore Sorensen summarized them as follows:
· Advisors must play their role in a crisis, but it is exclusively the President who ultimately bears the responsibility.
The majority of Kennedy's advisors – both civilian and military – wanted to attack Cuba at that time.
Only through Kennedy's sober analysis and his probing questions could alternatives and dangers be highlighted that were essential in determining the consequences.
· It is necessary to understand how an opponent thinks; furthermore, communication channels must remain open.
Driving an opponent into a corner without keeping diplomatic channels open that allow understanding of the opponent's situation could prove to be disastrous.
· The United States is dependent on allies.
Kennedy acted therefore because the NATO, further allies as well as the opinion of the world had supported him.
· A certain period of time is necessary for making good decisions.
If it is a matter of life or death, a politician cannot allow the media to pressure him into taking action.
The fact that a week passed in which all involved factors had been examined and weighed as carefully as possible was crucial for the outcome.
But would such a time frame for deliberation even exist today, given the current mass media?
Robert McNamara emphasized that it was necessary to put oneself in the opponent's position.
In one of the scenes in the film that was heavily criticized, McNamara explains to a war-hungry admiral that the naval blockade that Kennedy imposed on Cuba was primarily intended to send a signal to Premier Khrushchev about Kennedy's intention, and was not meant as a means to stop certain Soviet ships.
Could Kennedy have acted even more calmly?
After all, the United States had also stationed atomic warheads near the USSR.
Khrushchev's decision to station missiles in Cuba was merely a reflection of this policy.
Yet Kennedy showed concern regarding the consequences that the stationing of Soviet rockets in Cuba would have had for Berlin.
The pressure of atomic weapons on Cuba would have further complicated the defense of Berlin, which was part of Khrushchev's strategy.
„Ultimately, the Berlin crisis was resolved by the outcomes of the Cuban crisis,“ claimed historian Ernest May.
„Soon it will be too late,“ was a widely used argument that Kennedy heard from his advisors.
The advisors wanted to attack Cuba while the rockets – as they assumed – were en route to Cuba by sea.
A US force of about 180,000 men was prepared for an invasion; there were even plans for a rapid bombardment, which would have been larger in scale than the NATO attack in Kosovo sixty years later. „It took me thirty years,“ said McNamara, „to find out that there were already atomic weapons on Cuba: 162 warheads, and of those, 90 strategic nuclear warheads.“
McNamara received this information on the occasion of a meeting with Fidel Castro.
He asked Castro the following three questions: 1) Did you know about it?
2) If so, what did you recommend?
3) What would have been the consequences for Cuba?
Castro replied: „I knew about it.
And I explicitly recommended the use of atomic weapons.
I knew that this would have led to the destruction of Cuba.”
Castro and – to a greater extent – his comrade Che Guevara were ready to let Cuba burn to ashes, so that their country would become a martyr in the struggle for the world revolution!
An invasion would thus have potentially resulted in the death of 80 million Americans and the destruction of Cuba, simply because the Kennedy administration lacked sufficient knowledge of the facts (a situation that often occurs when a politician has to make a decision alone).
McNamara is firmly convinced that an invasion „undoubtedly“ would have led to a Soviet atomic attack against the USA.
Chruschtschow's control over the Soviet military in Cuba was indeed limited: planes of the type U2 flying over Cuban airspace were shot at despite explicit instructions to the contrary from the chairman.
A difficult question to answer, which did not arise during this debate at Harvard, is the following: What would have happened if the adversary had not been Chruschtschow, who distinguished himself during the crisis by more rational behavior, but rather an opponent of the type Saddam Hussein, Kim Jong Il, or a fundamentalist?
Given the spread of atomic weapons, this danger could one day become reality.
Today's discussions about limited missile defense and the threat of atomic blackmail by rogue states should be conducted in the light of this terrible but quite realistic thought.
Harvard has posted a new Web site on the Internet, where the essential documents about the Cuban Crisis as well as about current atomic threats can be found: www.cubanmissilecrisis.org .
